HTML div and span Elements
HTML div and span elements are used to group and style elements on a webpage.

HTML div Element
The div element is a block-level element used to group elements for styling or layout purposes. It is a generic container element that can be used to group any type of content.

HTML span Element
The span element is an inline element used to group inline elements for styling purposes. It is used to apply styles to a specific part of text or other inline elements.

HTML Code Example

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>HTML div and span Elements</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- div element -->
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- span element -->
  <p>This is a <span class="highlight">highlighted</span> text.</p>
</body>
</html>


CSS Code Example

.container {
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

.highlight {
  color: red;
  font-weight: bold;
}


Real-time Examples
1. Grouping elements: The div element can be used to group elements together for styling or layout purposes, such as creating a container for a header or footer.
2. Styling text: The span element can be used to apply styles to specific parts of text, such as highlighting important keywords or adding tooltips.

Questions and Answers
Q1: What is the purpose of the div element?
A1: The div element is used to group elements for styling or layout purposes.

Q2: What is the difference between div and span elements?
A2: The div element is a block-level element, while the span element is an inline element.

Q3: Can you use div elements inside span elements?
A3: No, div elements cannot be used directly inside span elements, as div is a block-level element and span is an inline element.

Q4: How can you style div and span elements using CSS?
A4: You can style div and span elements using CSS by selecting the elements and applying styles such as colors, fonts, padding, margin, and borders.

Q5: Can you use span elements to group block-level elements?
A5: No, span elements are used to group inline elements, not block-level elements. To group block-level elements, you should use div elements.